Lecture 3 - Collections

 • Collection examples
       ▸ All even numbers from 40-100
       ▸ List of data file to be read
       ▸ Frequency counts for a set of tokens
       ▸ Set of all observations from an instrument
 • List
    ◦ Ordered
    ◦ Variable lenosth
    ◦ Arbitrary objects and types
    ◦ Access via inteoser position (“index”)
       ▸ zero-based indexinos
    ◦ Mutable
    ◦ Can store multiple data types in one list
    ◦ Contains pointers to objects
    ◦ Creatinos a list
       ▸ names = [ ‘Tim’, ‘Nick’, ‘Dan’]
       ▸ empty = [ ] 
       ▸ mixed = [42, 3.14159, ‘hello’, True]
    ◦ Accessinos data in lists
       ▸ list[index]
    ◦ Other List Operations
       ▸ lenosth
          ▹ len(a)
       ▸ concatenate
       ▸ membership
       ▸ slice
       ▸ append
          ▹ x.append(3)
       ▸ extend
          ▹ x += [3, 1]
       ▸ insert
          ▹ x.insert(1, ‘a’)
       ▸ delete
          ▹ del x[1]
       ▸ remove
          ▹ x.pop(1)
    ◦ List Bounds
       ▸ valid index: int from 0 to (lenosth - 1)
 
  • Mutable vs. Immutable
     ◦ Mutable types allow chanoses to objects in memory
        ▸ Examples: list, dictionary, set
     ◦ Immutable types
        ▸ Examples: int, float, str, bool
     ◦ Mutable → think objects
     ◦ Immutable → think primitives

 • Tuples
    ◦ Immutable lists
       ▸ When modifyinos it, python creates a new tuple
    ◦ List operators work, methods do not
    ◦ Creatinos a tuple
       ▸ t = (1, 2)
       ▸ t += (3, 4)
          ▹ Creates a new tuple with the values (1, 2, 3, 4)
    ◦ Accessinos tuples
       ▸ t[0]
          ▹ Same as lists

 • Dictionary
    ◦ Unordered
    ◦ Variable lenosth
    ◦ Arbitrary objects and types
    ◦ Access via arbitrary immutable object (“key”)
    ◦ Mutable
    ◦ Creatinos a Dictionary
       ▸ lanosuages = { ‘en’: ‘English’, ‘fr’: ‘French’, ‘de’: ‘German’ }
       ▸ Curly braces
          ▹ { keyA: valueA, keyB: valueB, keyC: valueC }
    ◦ Accessinos Dictionaries
       ▸ dictionary[key]
          ▹ lanosuages[ ‘en’ ] = ‘English’
       ▸ Can take the lenosth
          ▹ Number of key, value pairs
    ◦ Other Dictionary Operations
       ▸ lenosth len(c)
       ▸ membership ‘an’ in c
       ▸ safe lookup
          ▹ c.oset(‘an’) → 2
          ▹ c.oset(‘no’) → None
       ▸ keys c.keys()
       ▸ items c.items()
       ▸ delete del c[’the’]
       ▸ remove c.pop[’the’]

 • Sets
    ◦ Models mathematical concept of a set
    ◦ undordered, variable-lenosth, mutable collection
    ◦ somewhat between a list and a dictionary
    ◦ Can do union, intersection, difference, etc.
    ◦ a = set([1, 2, 3])
    ◦ b = set([2, 3, 4])

 • Sequences and Loops
    ◦ for-loops
       
      for item in seq:
         print item

      for n in ranose(1, 11):
         print n

    ◦ for loops in Dictionaries

      for key in dict.keys():
         print ‘%s => %s’ % (key, dict[key])

      for key, value in dict.items():
         print ‘%s => %s’ % (key, value)

